## âš ï¸ Safety Note â€“ Breaker Isolation

Before installing or moving solar panels, **disable all breakers** in the system. This isolates the charge controller and battery bank, preventing any risk of live connections while routing or securing cables.

This same step was emphasized during the **Phase 2 system proof** process, and it remains critical here. Even in a temporary setup, proper breaker isolation ensures safe handling and prevents accidental energization.

## âš ï¸ Universal Safety Note â€“ Battery Awareness

Before starting Step:3, Itâ€™s important to recognize that **batteries are always live**. Even with breakers switched off and fuses installed, the battery terminals store energy and must be treated as an active power source.

* Never place tools or conductive objects on top of a battery.

* Avoid bridging the positive and negative terminals â€” doing so will throw sparks, can weld the tool in place, and may destroy the battery or start a fire.

* While a direct short usually wonâ€™t shock you, it can cause serious equipment damage or injury.

Keep this in mind throughout Phase 3 and beyond: **the battery is never â€œoff.â€**

## âš ï¸ Safety Note â€“ Battery & Inverter Wiring

When connecting inverters directly to a battery, always **install a fuse on the positive lead** sized for the inverterâ€™s expected draw (200A in this case). Without this protection, a short circuit or wiring error could instantly destroy the inverter â€” or worse, cause fire or battery damage.

Remember: the **battery itself is always energized.** Even with breakers and fuses in place, improper tool placement across the terminals can weld tools, start fires, or permanently damage the battery

## âš ï¸ Safety Note â€“ Hardwiring AC Power Strips

When modifying a power strip to be hardwired into an inverter:

* Always confirm **wire polarity** (hot, neutral, ground) before connecting to the inverter.

## âš ï¸ Safety Note â€“ First Power-On

When energizing a system for the first time:

* Always bring circuits online **step by step** â€” never all at once.

* Stand clear of battery terminals and inverter connections during initial energization.

* Keep a **fire extinguisher** on hand (rated for electrical fires) as a precaution.

* If anything smells of burning insulation, heats rapidly, or trips protection devices immediately â€” **shut down and troubleshoot before continuing.**

## âš ï¸ Safety Reinforcements

Phase 3 emphasized several critical safety practices:

* Always disable breakers before routing new connections.

* Batteries are **always live** â€” tools must never bridge terminals.

* Fuse the inverter positive lead to prevent catastrophic failure.

* Verify polarity and grounding when hardwiring AC circuits.

* Bring circuits online step-by-step during first power-up.

### **ğŸ’¡ Lessons & Philosophy**

* **Temporary vs Permanent:** Many installation choices (solar panel placement, battery enclosure, etc.) were intentionally temporary to prioritize speed and usability over permanence. Future phases will address long-term mounting, enclosures, and weatherproofing.

* **DC First:** By choosing to run lights and other accessories on 12V DC, the system philosophy prioritizes inverter capacity for when itâ€™s really needed. This approach makes scaling easier through battery expansion, rather than requiring more inverters.

* **Cable Discipline:** Consistent cable management and service loops across all phases has created a system that is not only functional, but also clear, maintainable, and easy to expand.
